\title{nanoGPT provides a simplified, highly optimized, and readable PyTorch implementation of the GPT-2 architecture, enabling efficient training and finetuning of language models from scratch or using pre-trained weights}
\author{PaperPilot}
\date{Drafted by PaperPilot for \emph{EMNLP 2026} on 2026-05-23}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
We present nanoGPT, a minimal yet highly optimized PyTorch implementation of the GPT-2 architecture designed to lower the barrier to entry for language model research and rapid experimentation. Existing open-source implementations frequently sacrifice readability for performance or vice versa, impeding reproducibility and accessibility for practitioners working outside large-scale compute environments. nanoGPT addresses this tension through a compact codebase—approximately 300 lines each for model definition and training loop—while incorporating modern efficiency techniques including Flash Attention, Distributed Data Parallel training, mixed-precision arithmetic, gradient accumulation, and cosine learning rate scheduling with warmup. We demonstrate that this implementation faithfully reproduces GPT-2 (124M parameters) on OpenWebText, achieving a validation loss of 2.85 in approximately four days on eight A100 GPUs. Integration with PyTorch 2.0's compilation framework reduces per-iteration wall-clock time from 250ms to 135ms, yielding substantial throughput improvements without architectural modification. Character-level models trained on Tiny Shakespeare converge to a validation loss of 1.47 in under three minutes on a single GPU. By prioritizing transparency, empirical reproducibility, and practical efficiency, nanoGPT serves as a tractable foundation for investigating scaling behavior, finetuning dynamics, and architectural modifications in controlled experimental settings.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
## Introduction

The rapid proliferation of large language models has fundamentally reshaped the landscape of natural language processing, yet the practical infrastructure required to train and finetune such models remains a persistent barrier to entry. Even models of moderate scale—on the order of hundreds of millions of parameters—impose substantial computational and engineering demands that can impede iterative experimentation, reproducibility studies, and pedagogical use. As the field increasingly relies on empirical validation of architectural choices, training dynamics, and scaling behavior, the absence of clean, auditable, and efficient reference implementations creates a reproducibility gap that is difficult to bridge through paper descriptions alone. This tension between the centrality of language model training to modern NLP research and the opacity of its practical execution motivates a renewed focus on accessible, well-engineered tooling.

Prior efforts to democratize language model training have generally fallen into one of two failure modes. On one end, production-grade frameworks prioritize scalability and feature completeness at the cost of readability, burying core logic beneath layers of abstraction that obscure the relationship between algorithmic choices and empirical outcomes. On the other end, educational implementations sacrifice performance to the point of impracticality, making it difficult to conduct experiments at meaningful scale. Neither regime adequately serves the researcher who needs to rapidly prototype a modification to the training objective, verify a scaling hypothesis, or finetune a pretrained checkpoint on a domain-specific corpus—all while maintaining confidence that the implementation faithfully reflects the intended procedure.

In this work, we present nanoGPT, a compact and highly optimized PyTorch implementation of the GPT-2 architecture designed to close this gap. The entire system is expressed in approximately 600 lines of core code spanning a model definition and a training loop, yet achieves competitive empirical results: reproducing GPT-2 (124M) on OpenWebText at a validation loss of approximately 2.85, and demonstrating substantial throughput gains through integration with PyTorch 2.0 compilation. We further provide utilities for dataset preparation, scaling law analysis, and finetuning from pretrained weights, offering a self-contained platform for empirical investigation of language model behavior across scales and domains.

\section{Related Work}
## Related Work

**Language Model Architectures and Pretraining.** nanoGPT builds directly on the GPT-2 Transformer architecture, which has become a standard testbed for studying autoregressive language modeling at scale. The broader ecosystem of instruction-tuned derivatives demonstrates the continued relevance of accessible GPT-style foundations: WizardLM \cite{arxiv_2304_12244} shows how open-domain instruction-following data can be generated at scale to finetune pretrained models effectively, while instruction tuning with GPT-4-generated data \cite{arxiv_2304_03277} underscores that high-quality supervision signals dramatically improve zero-shot generalization. These lines of work presuppose efficient, reproducible base model implementations of the kind nanoGPT provides.

**Efficient and Lightweight Model Training.** A recurring theme in the NLP community is reducing the computational burden of training and adapting large models without sacrificing downstream quality. Lightweight Transformer architectures for clinical NLP \cite{arxiv_2302_04725} illustrate that carefully engineered, smaller models can match or exceed much larger counterparts on specialized tasks—a philosophy closely aligned with nanoGPT's emphasis on simplicity and speed. Similarly, LIMIT \cite{arxiv_2311_13133} demonstrates that instruction tuning on smaller, curated datasets can match performance achieved with far larger corpora, reinforcing the value of lean training pipelines that nanoGPT facilitates.

**Domain-Specific Finetuning and Benchmarking.** Accessible training infrastructure is a prerequisite for rapid domain adaptation. FinGPT \cite{arxiv_2310_04793} exemplifies how open-source GPT implementations enable financial NLP practitioners to finetune models on specialized corpora with limited resources—a use case that benefits directly from readable, modifiable codebases. Evaluation frameworks such as the PPTC benchmark \cite{arxiv_2311_01767} further highlight the growing need for reproducible model checkpoints that can be quickly adapted and assessed across diverse task settings, motivating the kind of transparent, forkable implementation nanoGPT offers.

Together, these threads—scalable pretraining, efficient finetuning, and rigorous evaluation—situate nanoGPT as a practical foundation for empirical NLP research that prioritizes accessibility alongside competitive performance.

\section{Method}
## 3 Method

We implement a streamlined yet fully capable GPT-2 architecture in PyTorch, designed to balance readability with computational efficiency. The model follows the standard decoder-only Transformer formulation, comprising stacked blocks of causal multi-head self-attention and position-wise feed-forward (MLP) layers, with layer normalization applied prior to each sub-component. To support efficient training at scale, we incorporate several complementary techniques: distributed data-parallel training across multiple GPUs, mixed-precision computation via automatic casting to BFloat16, and gradient accumulation to simulate large effective batch sizes under memory constraints. The learning rate follows a cosine annealing schedule with a linear warmup phase, a widely adopted strategy for stabilizing early optimization and promoting convergence in large-scale language model training. Input text corpora are preprocessed offline into memory-mapped binary files of integer token IDs, enabling low-overhead data loading during training. Where available, we leverage PyTorch 2.0's graph compilation and Flash Attention to reduce per-iteration wall-clock time without altering model behavior. This design deliberately minimizes abstraction layers, keeping the full training loop and model definition each within approximately 300 lines of code, so that every modeling and optimization decision remains transparent and empirically auditable.

\section{Results}
\emph{Results section drafted from the repository's reported numbers and qualitative findings:}

nanoGPT successfully reproduces GPT-2 (124M) on OpenWebText, achieving a validation loss of ~2.85 in approximately 4 days on an 8x A100 40GB node. Smaller character-level models on Tiny Shakespeare achieve a 1.4697 validation loss in ~3 minutes on a single A100 GPU. Performance is significantly boosted by PyTorch 2.0's `torch.compile()`, reducing iteration time from ~250ms to 135ms.

\section{Discussion and Limitations}
\emph{Limitations the repository acknowledges or that follow from the method:}

The repository is explicitly stated as "very old and deprecated" (as of a Nov 2025 update), with a newer successor (`nanochat`) available. Future work includes investigating FSDP, evaluating zero-shot perplexities on standard benchmarks (e.g., LAMBADA, HELM), refining finetuning hyperparameters, and incorporating advanced embeddings (rotary, alibi).

